0.022763738,-0.059735656,0.12467415,-0.06275069,0.101657644,0.006378908,0.047182903,-0.026944324,-0.014088541,0.0037814202,-0.06440211,-0.017705685,-0.01978994,0.005207123,-0.0005756224,-0.075419545,0.08238388,-0.009401521,-0.026392097,-0.004440979,0.042423245,0.023938334,-0.009403911,-0.011295252,-0.016210202,0.024221858,-0.011160402,0.059580784,0.014936479,0.042429425,0.051134057,0.034328304,0.04016747,-0.023744738,-0.046609,0.008138474,0.017231256,-0.03732261,-0.06766708,0.03788268,0.046001952,0.02572135,-0.035972733,0.032070193,0.023121571,-0.03278081,0.013038853,0.016882412,0.029263845,0.024344107,-0.019306168,-0.021403648,-0.08800253,0.04215835,-0.0155589515,0.008301704,-0.027773846,2.8420257e-07,0.0014846519,0.02359799,-0.022203594,0.050032996,-0.018994426,-0.035523333,-0.041984357,-0.022097565,0.04474812,0.040375125,0.028132975,0.014372896,-0.0020384372,0.01581732,0.037501343,-0.036748737,-0.018752763,-0.06423424,-0.014233093,0.06845851,0.030449444,-0.00501315,0.043152917,-0.033495266,-0.010996329,-0.023267183,0.027081447,0.00037639547,-0.005317241,-0.0072321906,0.03084122,-0.0488065,0.0643692,-0.031407055,0.036333468,0.06976242,-0.0064546512,0.09062664,0.012952588,0.073650986,0.020514535,-0.04658827,0.002494565,0.04296212,0.051489532,0.031925302,-0.031678356,-0.05190482,0.014871422,-0.0063190213,-0.049776882,0.008763362,-0.069608964,0.0037034212,0.0321804,-0.015521973,0.00092571654,0.048343007,0.015947802,0.0435298,-0.029564817,0.035768725,0.0028856702,0.06400222,-0.021364769,-0.030772688,0.010153895,2.9561952e-34,-0.012495485,-0.015358156,0.025383696,-0.015830047,0.023006327,-0.04701077,-0.04269806,0.057118505,-0.0019615483,-0.02907458,0.0047755353]','Suppose you want to write a rule with a condition that payee mcc should be one of the MCCs in this object (additional_mcc). The logic then would be as follows: {"if": [ {"!!": {"var":"payee.mcc"}}, {"in": [ {"var":"payee.mcc"}, {"reduce": [ {"objectToArray": {"var": "observations.payeeVPA.account.customer.attribs.additional_mcc"}}, {"merge":[{"var":"current.mcc"}, {"var":"accumulator"}]}, []] } ]}, "payee.mcc not supplied" ]} Rationale: What we are doing here is taking out only mcc codes from the array of objects while ignoring the category and other keys.Result of the "reduce" operation will be [888, 889, 890] Since we want to perform this operation only if payee.mcc is supplied, we are wrapping this under a "truthy" ("!!") check, instead comparing it with null. Then we are using the "in" operation to look for "payee.mcc" inside that array. We are wrapping the whole "in" test within a "!" (negative) test, to get the opposite result as per the logic of the rule What do the [ ] (square brackets) after the merge operation are for?Those Empty brackets are initializers to "var: accumulator" in the "reduce" operations. if we had data like {"something": [888, 889, 890]}','{"Date": "2025-03-24", "DocName": "Rule Doc", "Page ID": 41, "Version": 5, "iTenantID": 17}');
