1.2 Transaction Class API
Class is introduced as a level at which risk is managed. It can be
a transaction identifier. So for distinguishing particular sets of
transactions based on customer category type i.e. Platinum /
Premium or bank type i.e. ABC Bank / XYZ Bank or based on
transaction mode i.e. UPI / CARD / ATM; these classes can be set
and based on the class identifier in the score request API, the
rules would be fired.
Additionally, at the class level, we can set the skip_processing
bit to configure settings related to risk scoring and real time
aggregations.
The API supports CRUD operations and the details on the same is
given below:
> `[POST /transaction_class]` to add a transaction class
> `[PUT /transaction_class/txnClassName]` to edit a transaction class
> `[DELETE /transaction_class/txnClassName]` to delete a transaction class
> `[GET /transaction_class/txnClassName]` to fetch a transaction class
> `[GET /transaction_class/byid/classid]` to fetch a transaction class by iclassid
> `[PUT /transaction_class/byid/classid]` to edit a transaction class by iclassid
> `[DELETE /transaction_class/byid/classid]`to delete transactionclass by iclassid
Note:
● update, delete and get methods of ''transaction_class'' require
transaction class name in the path variable such as
/transaction_class/UPI|API-TEST1 since ''|'' character is not
valid in urls, it is required to URLEncode that word. To do
that, select the word "UPI|API-TEST1" and right-click to see
and select option "EncodeURLComponent". It should turn into:
/transaction_class/UPI%7CAPI-TEST1
● also you can fetch, update and delete class by classid by
putting iclassid of that transaction class in the path
1.2.1 Transaction Class API - Example
{
"txnClassName": "UPI|API-TEST1",
"productID": 1,
"channelID": 1,
"decisionID": 61,
"payerMandatory": false,
