INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('API Masters & BNPL',6,'2025-03-24',120,'Profiles are computations which are evaluated on the basis
of historical data such as for the last 6 months, 3 months
or 1 month.In other words, profiles store historical
computations/attributes across multiple roots such as VPA,
Account, MCC, Location etc.
Computations/Attributes example:
▪ total value for last one month, 3 months etc.
▪ Last transaction date for Acc/VPA
▪ Count of country/state visited in last 30 days
Profile historical computations are done accounts/vpas with
their behaviour on payer and payee side of the transaction,
both depending on the requirement.
There are a total 7 levels at which the profile computation can be
configured.
- account (daily)
- account_monthly (monthly)
- account_weekly (weekly)
- mcc (mcc wise computation)
- vpa (daily)
- vpa_monthly (monthly)
- vpa_weekly (weekly)
- location (location wise computation)
Profile computations happen end of day on a date called
date, short for transaction date by doing profile run.We can
run profiles on a daily basis or for any specific date.
1.15.18 Profile run endpoint
POST: {{base_url_profiles}}/profiles
BODY:
{
"itenantid": 12,
"tdate": "2023-12-26"
}
Parameter Type Description
itenantid Integer tenant id for which profile is to be
run i.e 1,2,3,4
tdate String Date for which profile is to be run.
in YYYY-MM-DD format. This date
cannot exceed today. Profiles can be
run only for a tdate once.
120 |',17,'239f5b69-f6a2-4b09-adc7-2554dd5ef040');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('API Masters & BNPL',6,'2025-03-24',121,'1.15.19 Get Profile Logs endpoint
After a profile run , get logs to verify the details of
computation whether the run got successful or it failed.
Following endpoint is used to get logs for profiles.
GET: {{base_url_profiles}}/logs
1.15.20 Get Profile run status endpoint
GET Status request just shows the time of start run of
profile, time when profile run finishes and the date for
which profile was run. E.g:
{
"finished": "08/06/2023 21:56:25",
"started": "08/06/2023 21:55:18",
"tdate": "2023-06-03"
}
GET: {{base_url_profiles}}/status
In case there are older profile entries till the selected date
which is 2023-12-26 in this case, then we delete the profiles from
that day onward before triggering fresh profiles(current date gets
overwritten).
If you are running profiles without providing tdate then it will
check for which tdate profiles were run previously suppose the
previous tdate= ''2023-07-15'' then profiles will automatically run
for 2023-07-16.
1.15.21 RocksDB recon, delta recon, rocksdb refresh
Rocksdb Recon used to generate recon files from rocksdb.
These files can be used to check if the current profile data
available in analytical db is in sync with the one available
in rocks db.
POST: {{base_url_profiles}}/rocksdbrecon
Delta recon used to generate recon logs from the delta
table. This is used by Zala to debug any issue.
121 |',17,'16cadb88-6639-426f-b2e8-1738d9e7613b');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('API Masters & BNPL',6,'2025-03-24',122,'POST: {{base_url_profiles}}/deltarecon
Rocksdb Refresh used to send the latest profile entries for
each account / vpa id to rocks db. This is used if it
doesn’t happen automatically during the profile run process
or if any manual alteration is made in the profiles on
analytical db which needs to be send to rocks db.
POST: {{base_url_profiles}}/rocksdbrefresh
Sendtrigger is used to trigger score after profiles are
executed. This is used if it doesn’t happen automatically at
the end of profile run or if any manual alteration is made
in the profiles on analytical db which needs to be reflected
in score. This API is to be run after running the rocks db
refresh API.
1.15.22 Send trigger to Score endpoint
POST: {{base_url_profiles}}/sendtrigger
1.15.23 Trim tables endpoint
Trim tables need to be done when we want to validate the new
custom fields for previous dates and we do new backdated
transactions for those dates
POST: {{base_url_profiles}}/trim_tables
Suppose you want to compute profiles of tenant 12 where you
want totalCount of txns done where subtype is 552, to
compute profiles for subtype = 552 we will need to add this
field in requirements.ini of that tenant.
1.15.24 Get Requirements.INI
You can check requirements.ini for a tenant id by doing a
GET
GET: {{base_url_profiles}}/requirements/tenant_id
122 |',17,'065fda2e-1b96-4d39-946e-5f64694465b1');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('API Masters & BNPL',6,'2025-03-24',123,'Profiles need to have fields in requirements.ini (ask devops
team)to be captured in the purview table. Refer to the
Profiles SOP for a detailed overview SOP(profiles)
123 |',17,'8d4bb843-72e4-4941-b970-bcd6a2907d49');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('Rule Doc',5,'2025-03-24',1,'nIntroduction 1. Rules in Transaction Monitoring / Fraud Detection! ● Rules are a means to manage and identify risky actions ● Transaction monitoring refers to the monitoring of customer transactions, including assessing historical/current customer information and interactions to provide a complete picture of customer activity. This can include transfers, deposits, and withdrawals. ● Rules in transaction monitoring / fraud detections are logical checks or sets of conditions that help you decide if an activity is fraudulent or not. ● For e.g., Let’s assume, you know that a payment address belongs to a fraudster and needs to be blacklisted (blocked). Therefore, the most basic type of rule base on if/else logic could be: if payment address = deena@oksbi, then block transaction 11. Categorization of Rules in Drona Pay ● CATEGORY - Transaction ● MODE - Static/Dynamic ● SIDE - Payer/Payee/Both ● DIMENSION - Value based, Count based, IP based/ MCC Based/ Location based ● Batch - Daily batch, Weekly batch, Monthly batch',17,'409bbd87-5d25-42ee-9506-1f803c1445d7');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('Rule Doc',5,'2025-03-24',2,'III. Elements of Rules The concept of rules comprises three primary elements essential for its construction. These fundamental elements are: ● Rule Params ● Observer - Windows and Observation // Real-Time Aggregates ● Profiles // Historical Computation Rule API Sample { "mst_type": "rules", "vcrulename": ""HIGH_DEBIT_TXN_AMT"", "idecisionid": DECISION ID, "vcruledescription": null, "vcruledetail": "{ \"if\": [ { \"!=\": [ { \"var\": \"rule_params.values.value_threshold\" }, null ] }, { \"if\": [ { \"and\": [ { \"!=\": [ { \"var\": \"observations.payerVPA.account\" }, null ] }, { \">=\": [ { \"var\": \"observations.payer_account_pt24h_txn_value\" }, { \"var\": \"rule_params.values.value_threshold\" } ] } ] }, { \"dict\": [ [ \"status\", true ], [ \"score\", { \"var\": \"rule_params.fail.score\" } ], { \"var\": \"rule_params.fail.remarks\" }, [ \"workflow\", \"Score\" ], [ \"remarks\", { \"var\": \"rule_params.fail.remarks\" } ] ] }, { \"dict\": [ [ \"status\", false ], [ \"score\", { \"var\": \"rule_params.success.score\" } ], [ \"workflow\", \"\" ], [ \"remarks\", { \"var\": \"rule_params.success.remarks\" } ] ] } ] }, { \"dict\": [ [ \"status\", false ], [ \"score\", { \"var\": \"rule_params.error.score\" } ], [ \"workflow\", \"\" ], [ \"remarks\", { \"var\": \"rule_params.error.remarks\" } ] ] } ] }"", "vcruleparams": "{\"type\":\"Alert\",\"workflow\":\"Score\",\"success\":{\"score\":0,\"remarks\":\"\"},\"fail\":{\"remarks\":\"Payer\",\"scor e\":70},\"error\":{\"remarks\":\"error in rule config\",\"score\":0},\"values\":{\"value_threshold\":100000}}", "vcruleorder": "{\"FailedRule\":1801,\"StartRule\":1,\"SuccessRule\":1801}", "bcustom": true,',17,'49e1ef78-dcfd-44a4-8dfd-86a7571d0f71');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('Rule Doc',5,'2025-03-24',3,'"bdelete": false, "bactive": true, "iuserid": null, "action": "A" /// A = Add, M = Modify, X = Delete "StartRule": 1 ( Mandatory only for the first rule of rule sequence, for the rest this tag can be removed or set to value >2 )} Path: {{base_url}}/arb/{{rules_topic}}/rule_id rules_topic : this is set as envt_tenantid Item Datatype Description mst_type string set to “rules” vcrulename String Rule Name char - 200 idecisionid Integer Decision ID vcruledetail String JSON logic of rule converted into String vcruleparams Array JSON for setting success, fail, error and threshold details converted into string bcustom Boolean Set to True for rules coded with JSONLogic. Set to False for rules coded with Python bactive Boolean set to True if rule is active vcruleorder String JSON which specifies rule sequence in case of success/failure 1. FirstRule A : { “FailedRule” : X, “SuccessRule”: X, “StartRule” : 1} 2. AlertRule A: { “FailedRule” : X, “SuccessRule”: X} 3. Block Rule A: { “FailedRule” : -1, “SuccessRule”: X) 4. Last Rule A: { “FailedRule” : -1, “SuccessRule”: -1) Converted into',17,'7c0cd655-bf83-4aa9-bda9-ccaecd28fa9a');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('Rule Doc',5,'2025-03-24',4,'String action String A - Add M - Modify X - Delete StartRule Integer Value = 1 for the first Rule of the Rule Sequence For rest, this field can be skipped Rule Params ● Rule Params is defined as a JSON code that helps us to define multiple thresholds for rules. ● Thresholds for a rule are defined below "values" object For e.g., consider the "High Value Transaction" rule, which triggers an alert whenever a transaction exceeds 50,000. In this instance, the threshold value is set at 50,000. ● "type" determines whether it should be an ALERT based or BLOCK based or BRANCH rule (Link to Rule Order) ● "fail.score" and “fail.remarks” determine the score and remarks that need to be displayed when the rule is triggered. ● "success.score" and “success.remarks” determine the score and remarks that needs to be displayed when the rule is not triggered and passed in evaluation',17,'4d7b5e47-d778-4462-b9df-eb9cae256441');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('Rule Doc',5,'2025-03-24',5,'● "error.score" and “error.remarks” determines the score and remarks that needs to be displayed when the rule is incorrectly configured ● Sample Rule Param: { "type": "Block", "workflow": "Score", "success": { "score": 0, "remarks": "" }, "fail": { "remarks": "High Value Cross Border ATM", "score": 50 }, "error": { "remarks": "error in rule config", "score": 0 }, "values": { "value_threshold": 50000, “count_thresold”: 10 } } ● Similarly depending on the requirement, you can define array based thresholds under the values section. Types of arrays based thresholds are as follows: a. Single-Dimensional Array: A single-dimensional array is a linear collection of elements. E.g., "values": { "mcc_array": [',17,'88f21b6a-8127-4ad7-bd66-b6e23f1a9c48');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('Rule Doc',5,'2025-03-24',6,'"4576", "5634" ] } b. Multi-Dimensional Array: A multi-dimensional array can be specifically a two-dimensional array or a list of dictionaries. E.g., "values": { "mcc_array": [ { "mcc_value": 5469, "mcc_threshold": 25200 }, { "mcc_value": 2568, "mcc_threshold": 50000 }, { "mcc_value": 4698, "mcc_threshold": 100000 } ] } ● In the above-mentioned example, the outer array is named "mcc_array" and each element of this array is a dictionary containing two key-value pairs: "mcc_value" and "mcc_threshold".',17,'68b600be-a01a-4da5-b8bb-98c89c4392be');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('Rule Doc',5,'2025-03-24',7,'Observations ● Observations are real-time aggregates computed from a window of transactions for a party (Account/VPA) as a Payer/Payee or for a transaction attribute. One window can have multiple observations linked to it. ● Conceptually, a window is a raw dataset where the selectExpr is recorded and stored for each id and grouped by each payer/payee identifier. Observation is the query result by applying the appropriate aggregate function for that data-set computed for a time interval and returned for the party as of the current txn ● Observations are thus processed in sequential order of `[ wid, oid]`. ● Observations are added to the object as and when they are computed. Window and Observation Logic can refer to any observation computed before itself. ● Observations are always defined for a subset of the time window (P1D/P2D/PT24H/PT1H/PT2H etc.) that you have previously configured for its associated window ● Under a defined window, the observations can be configured with time frames such as PT5M,PT15M,PT30M,PT60M,PT1H,PT4H i.e ISO 8601 format ● Possible aggregation types are COUNT/COUNT_IF/ SUM, SUM_IF/MAX/AVG/COUNT_UNIQUE/COUNT_ALIKE/LAST_KNOWN. Sample observation: { "observationId": 1, "observationName": "payer_m30_txn_count", "observationDescription": "Count of txns in last 30 mins for a VPA Id as Payer", "windowId": 1,',17,'a9dd4d81-8757-4c56-8708-d8aa419fc70a');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('Rule Doc',5,'2025-03-24',8,'"whereExpr": null, "groupByExpr": { "cat": [ { "var": "observations.payerVPA.vpaId" } ] }, "observationDuration": "PT30M", "observationCount": null, "aggregationType": "COUNT", "recordStatus": 0 } For creating real time aggregates, refer to the documentation on Observer. Profiles ● Profiles are computations which are evaluated on the basis of historical data such as for the last 6 months, 3 months or 1 month. ● In other words, profiles store historical computations/attributes across multiple roots such as VPA, Account, MCC, Location etc. ● Computations/Attributes example: ▪ total value for last one month, 3 months etc.',17,'a3390236-d9b4-44e6-90ef-ee8d53a2951f');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('Rule Doc',5,'2025-03-24',9,'▪ Last transaction date for Acc/VPA ▪ Count of country/state visited in last 30 days ● Profile historical computations are done for payer and payee side, both depending on the requirement. Also, the computations provide the data of payer-as-payee behavior and vice-versa. ● Sample profile data: "profile": { "payeracc": { "val": { "totalValue": { "p7d": { "payee": 8452042.0, "payer": 52000.0 }, "p15d": { "payee": 46476542.09, "payer": 52000.0 }, "p30d": { "payee": 46476542.09, "payer": 52000.0 }, "payee": 46476542.09, "payer": 52000.0 } ● Profile tables can be found in the Profiles schema of FRM DB. For configuring a new profile field, ensure it is added in the “profiles.metadata” table with required configuration. ● Metadata is also found in the profile schema. ● Steps to configure metadata are mentioned in profiles SOP. URL : SOP(profiles)',17,'7c3335d7-fd01-43fc-9a44-05d43cb4ed21');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('Rule Doc',5,'2025-03-24',10,'Reference in Rule - JSON ● As discussed, rules are JSON code consisting of a set of logical checks/conditions. ● These logical checks/conditions as per the requirement use values from the following: ▪ Rule Params ▪ Observations - computed observations along with master details (payerVPA, payeeVPA) & score request objects ( txn, payer, payee) ▪ Profile Computations ▪ Rule processing dictionary [ status, score, workflow, remarks/side , rule-order (in case of Branch rules)] ● Therefore, to fetch the values from any of the above-mentioned so that logical checks/conditions can be evaluated in rule JSON, the correct reference needs to be provided. ● To fetch the required threshold values from rule params, always use the following reference in rule JSON: { "var": "rule_params.values.single_txn_amt_val_threshold" } ● To fetch the required observation values from rule params, use the following reference in rule JSON: { "var": "observations.instructed_amount"',17,'49403acb-ced2-48ea-9e9e-a22ebf79a202');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('Rule Doc',5,'2025-03-24',11,'} ● To retrieve the necessary profile computations from profiles, refer to the following JSON structure within the rules. Additionally, please be aware that in generic score instances, referring to "val" is no longer necessary, as it was the case in previous non-generic instances. Payer Side: Payer Behavior: { "var":"profile.payeracc.totalValue.p15d.payer" } Payer as Payee Behavior: { "var":"profile.payeracc.totalValue.p15d.payee" } Payee Side: Payee Behavior: { "var":"profile.payeeacc.totalValue.p15d.payee" } Payee as Payer Behavior: { "var":"profile.payeeacc.totalValue.p15d.payer" }',17,'fcb7513a-d0e6-406e-b4af-a169c9e9bebb');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('Rule Doc',5,'2025-03-24',12,'Null Checks ● Before scripting the logical checks/conditions in JSON code for the rule, the null checks need to be provided in the starting if any of the following is being used: ▪ Rule Params ▪ Non-Mandatory fields ▪ Profile Computations ▪ Observations (Master-data) ● Sample null-checks are as follows: { "and": [ { "!=": [ { "var": "observations.payerVPA.account" }, null // Functional Check ] }, { "!=": [ { "var": "profile.payeracc.val.activationDate" }, null // Profile Check ] }, { "!=": [ { "var": "rule_params.values.minkyc" },',17,'276da98e-ed4c-43dd-a845-325c3912f3b7');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('Rule Doc',5,'2025-03-24',13,'null // Rule Params (Threshold) check ] } ] } JSON Structure - Rules ● Rules are categorized as of two types: ▪ Single-threshold Rules ▪ Multi-threshold Rules I. Single-Threshold Rule ● As the name suggests, single-threshold rules have all the logical checks/conditions on the basis of only one defined threshold in rule params. ● Sample rule logic: If {( B!=null), If {(A!=null AND A>B), return dict{status: True, score: Fail Score,workflow: Workflow_Name, remarks: Fail Remarks}, else dict{status:False,score: Success Score,workflow : “”,remarks : success remarks}} } else dict[status: False,score: Error Score,workflow:,””,remarks: Error Remarks]} ● Sample single-threshold rule:',17,'2d3bf1fe-1930-4076-ad39-5363a121bdef');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('Rule Doc',5,'2025-03-24',14,'{ "if": [ { "!=": [ { "var": "rule_params.values.value_threshold" }, null ] }, { "if": [ { "and": [ { "!=": [ { "var": "observations.payerVPA.account" }, null ] }, { ">=": [ { "var": "observations.payer_account_pt24h_txn_value" }, { "var": "rule_params.values.value_threshold" } ] } ] }, { "dict": [ [ "status", true ], [ "score",',17,'215812b1-f282-4418-9e65-0d9e24521e3c');
