6. Admin
6.1 User Management
User Management provides the system administrator Identity access
and user management features. The Admin user can view all the
users that are currently associated with the system.
The Admin user has the ability to create, edit and delete users
from the system.
Upon clicking on the Edit button under the action column the admin
can change various basic account details of the chosen user
profile. The Basic Details include all the general information
including:
● Name
● e-mail
● designation
● contact number
● mobile number
● address
The account details include all the relevant account details like:
● user name
● password
● User Role: God, Risk Analyst, DB, Branch, QC, IT and MIS.
40 |',17,'2e18556a-115f-41eb-a766-df8ce5943c18');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('User Manual',1,'2025-03-24',41,'● User Group: User can be grouped under a single or a
combination of groups
6.2 Email Scheduler
The Email Scheduler functionality can be used to schedule reports
to be sent to users or emailIDs at a regular interval. All the
reports available in the UI can be scheduled using this
functionality.
6.2.1 Creating a Email Schedule
Steps to create a new email schedule:
● Click on the “CREATE NEW SCHEDULE” button.
● Choose the report that you want to schedule using the Menu,
Sub Menu and Report fields
● Choose a Frequency at which you would want to receive this
report by choosing Frequency, Day and Time
● In case of Weekly and Monthly, choose a Day when you want to
receive the report. In case of Weekly, Day should be between
0 to 7 and in case of Monthly, Day should be between 0 to 30
● Users who need to be added to the schedule can be selected
from dropdown or a custom email id can be added by “ADD
CUSTOM EMAIL” button
● Under the Attribs section all the mandatory fields need to be
filled as per selected report. Period field needs to have the
negative value of number of days for which you want the
report from today for eg. -1 if you want the report of date =
yesterday
● Example screenshot can be seen below,
41 |',17,'95875acb-ec3b-42c3-a1c5-2c9434ebe4da');
INSERT INTO agents.user_manual(doc_name,version,date,pageid,page_content,itenantid,docid) VALUES ('User Manual',1,'2025-03-24',42,'6.3 Admin Reports
Under the Admin reports we have below reports available for the
user to download for a specified date range. An admin user can
monitor items such as daily count of transactions processed,
edits/deletes/additions of rules by all user and other changes in
all master configurations
● Txn Count Report
● Audit Report - Rules
● Audit Report - Class
● Audit Report - Decision
● Audit Report - Windows
● Audit Report - Observations
● Audit Report - User
● Audit Report - Metadata
● Audit Report - Activity Log
42 |',17,'c77bed53-3c0d-472a-ac67-0ca545bf9670');

INSERT INTO masters.sysconfig values('agents','Agents config',0,'[
  {
    "agent": "caseagentv1",
    "doctype": "RuleSpecificL1Action",
    "input_data": [
      "RuleSpecificL1Action",
      "RuleID",
      "CaseID",
      "BatchDate",
      "itenantid",
      "iaccountid",
      "icustomerid"
    ],
    "vectorstore": {
      "data": [
        "prerequisites.AccountMaster",
        "prerequisites.MonthlyProfile"
      ],
      "filter": [
        "RuleID",
        "RuleSpecificL1Action"
      ],
      "metadata": [
        "RuleSpecificL1Action",
        "ruleid",
        "caseid",
        "batchdate",
        "itenantid"
      ],
      "embedding_model": "sentence-transformers/all-mpnet-base-v2",
      "cnt_similarities": 2
    },
    "model_config": {
      "role": "user",
      "params": {
        "temperature": 0
      }
    },
    "prerequisites": [
      {
        "conn": "txndb",
        "name": "MonthlyProfile",
        "type": "DB",
        "query": "WITH flattened_data AS ( select am.*, jt.path, jt.value from (SELECT * FROM profiles.account_monthly where itenantid=:itenantid and iaccountid=:iaccountid order by itenantid,tdate desc LIMIT 1 )am CROSS JOIN LATERAL( WITH RECURSIVE json_tree AS ( SELECT key, value, key AS path FROM jsonb_each(am.val) as e UNION ALL select t.key, t.value, json_tree.path || ''.'' || t.key as path from json_tree CROSS join lateral jsonb_each(json_tree.value) as t where jsonb_typeof(json_tree.value) = ''object'' ) select path, value from json_tree where jsonb_typeof(value) <> ''object'') as jt), transformed_json AS ( select fd.iaccountid, fd.tdate, fd.itenantid, jsonb_object_agg(fd.path, fd.value) as transformed_json from flattened_data fd group by fd.iaccountid,fd.tdate,fd.itenantid ) select ( select jsonb_object_agg( coalesce(m.vcdescription,kv.key), kv.value ) from jsonb_each(tj.transformed_json) kv left join profiles.metadata m on kv.key = m.vcpath ) AS final_json from transformed_json tj;",
        "params": [
          {
            "name": "iaccountid",
            "valueField": "input_data.iaccountid"
          },
          {
            "name": "itenantid",
            "valueField": "input_data.itenantid"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "conn": "txndb",
        "name": "AccountMaster",
        "type": "DB",
